treatment of the city and the soul evolves throughout the dialogue and can be appreciated only by considering the Republic in its entirety. He shows that the views expressed in the early parts of the text do not represent Plato's final judgment on these subjects but are in fact dialectical "moments" intended to be both partial and provisional. Books 5-7 of the Republic are, he maintains, meant to revise and improve upon books 2-4. Similarly, he sees the usually neglected books 8-10 as advancing beyond the thoughts presented in the previous books. Paying particular attention to these later books, Roochnik details, for instance, how the stories of the "mistaken" regimes, which are often seen as unimportant, are actually crucial in Plato's account of the soul.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy.  aAncient Greece.  aAncient Greek literature.  aAncient Greek philosophy.  aAristotle.  aEpistemology.  aGreek philosophy.  aMetaphysics.  aPlato's Republic analysis.  aPlato's Republic interpretation.  aPlato's Republic understanding.  aPlato's Republic.  aPlato.  aPolitical philosophy.  aRoman philosophy.  aThe Republic.  aancient greek philosophy.  aancient greek thought.  abooks for classicists.  aclassical philosophy.  aclassicists.  aclassics studies.  ahistory of philosophy.  ahistory of politics.  aintroduction to greek philosophy greek.  aplato commentary.  aplato dialectic.  aplato philosophy.  aplato political theory.  aplatonism.  apolitical theorists.  apolitical theory.  apsychology of democracy.  ascholars of the classical world.  atheory of politics.  atripatriate city.  aunderstanding platoist philosophy.  autopian scholars.  autopian studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Bac